    {
      "id": "T-20260428-1000",
      "title": "Patch OpenClaw Telegram callback spinner lane",
      "status": "active",
      "statusLabel": "\ud83d\udd04 \u8fdb\u884c\u4e2d",
      "notes": "The first callback-lane patch was not enough, so I added a second deeper patch in `/opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/dist/extensions/telegram/bot-msflwCEW.js`: `answerCallbackQuery` now uses a direct unthrottled fetch path instead of the general Telegram bot API throttler. Next step is restart + one fresh tap canary.",
      "requestedAt": null,
      "updatedAt": "2026-04-28 02:56",
      "owner": "JOSH 2.0"
    },
    {
      "id": "T-20260428-999",
      "title": "Improve Telegram button feedback UX",
      "status": "active",
      "statusLabel": "\ud83d\udd04 \u8fdb\u884c\u4e2d",
      "notes": "Fresh live tap test confirms the visible ack path works, but native spinner clearing still fails. New root-cause finding from heartbeat inspection: OpenClaw\u2019s `getTelegramSequentialKey()` currently puts callback queries on the same per-chat sequential lane as normal direct messages, so busy chat work can delay `answerCallbackQuery` long enough to miss Telegram\u2019s timeout. Most promising fix is a local Telegram extension patch that gives callback queries their own fast lane before normal chat processing.",
      "requestedAt": null,
      "updatedAt": "2026-04-28 02:37",
      "owner": "JOSH 2.0"
    },
    {
      "id": "T-20260427-971",
      "title": "Clean stale task drift",
      "status": "active",
      "statusLabel": "\ud83d\udd04 \u8fdb\u884c\u4e2d",
      "notes": "Heartbeat self-maintenance applied cleanly but recurring task-audit noise persists after apply, so the underlying timestamp/drift source still needs a real fix rather than more pruning.",
      "requestedAt": null,
      "updatedAt": "2026-04-28 02:09",
      "owner": "JOSH 2.0"
    },
    {
      "id": "T-20260428-996",
      "title": "Verify post-restart button behavior",
      "status": "active",
      "statusLabel": "\ud83d\udd04 \u8fdb\u884c\u4e2d",
      "notes": "Root cause is now specific: Telegram updates are sequentialized by chat/thread, and callback queries share the same lane as normal direct-chat turns. When this direct lane is busy or stuck in a tool loop, the callback waits behind it and `answerCallbackQuery` misses Telegram's timeout window. Fresh sweep: gateway is healthy/listening on 127.0.0.1:18790, but `openclaw status` timed out again after 8s, which reinforces the direct-lane/control-plane stall theory.",
      "requestedAt": null,
      "updatedAt": "2026-04-28 02:06",
      "owner": "JOSH 2.0"
    },
    {
      "id": "T-20260428-994",
      "title": "Fix Telegram button UX end-to-end",
      "status": "active",
      "statusLabel": "\ud83d\udd04 \u8fdb\u884c\u4e2d",
      "notes": "Continued audit confirms a repeating pattern beyond individual taps: direct-session stuck warnings, callback-answer expiry, recurring local gateway timeout health-check failures, and repeated Telegram provider restarts. Latest quick sweep shows the gateway is up while `openclaw status` still intermittently hangs, so the issue looks more like control-plane responsiveness/queueing than bad button payloads.",
      "requestedAt": null,
      "updatedAt": "2026-04-28 02:06",
      "owner": "JOSH 2.0"
    }
